Day45_harry.py we have created this file first
name = input("Enter your name:")

def welcome():
    print("Hey,you are welcome by",name)

def goodbye():
    print("Hey,Goodbye!! for now. We will meet tommorow")

print(__name__)
if __name__ == "__main__":
    welcome()
    goodbye()

# When we run that code from this module then we will shown that print(__name__) will show output as __main__

Output if we run code from this file:-
Enter your name: Ankit
__main__
Hey,you are welcome by  Ankit
Hey,Goodbye!! for now. We will meet tommorow

Day45_main.py
# if "__name__ == __main__" in python:-
# The if __name__ == "__main__" idiom is a common pattern used in Python Scripts to determine whether the script is being run directly or being imported as a module into another script

import Day45_harry 
Day45_harry.welcome()
Day45_harry.goodbye()

# When we run that code from this module then we will shown that print(__name__) will show output as Day45_harry

